data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compiled and ran without issues. On this 64-bit system, `nint` is 8 bytes. The syntax is straightforward:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types (aliases for `System.IntPtr`/`System.UIntPtr`). They work with `stackalloc` just like any other unmanaged type.
